What is an AWS IAM Access Key?
An IAM Access Key is a set of long-term credentials used to interact with AWS programmatically. Unlike a username and password (used for the Management Console), access keys allow the AWS CLI, SDKs, and APIs to verify your identity and permissions.
     What is VPC Peering?
VPC Peering is a networking connection between two Virtual Private Clouds (VPCs) that allows them to route traffic to each other using private IP addresses. Once peered, instances in both VPCs behave as if they are on the same local network.
Key Features
Private Connectivity: Traffic stays on the AWS Global Backbone. It never traverses the public internet, making it highly secure.

No Single Point of Failure: It is not a gateway or a physical appliance; there are no bandwidth bottlenecks or hardware risks.

Cross-Account & Cross-Region: You can peer VPCs across different AWS accounts and different geographical regions (Inter-Region Peering).

Cost-Efficient: There is no charge for setting up a peering connection. You only pay standard data transfer rates (inter-AZ or inter-region).
What is AWS Transit Gateway?
AWS Transit Gateway (TGW) is a network hub that allows you to connect thousands of Virtual Private Clouds (VPCs) and on-premises networks through a single central point.

Think of it as a "Cloud Router." Instead of creating a messy "web" of individual peering connections, everything plugs into the Transit Gateway, which manages all the traffic in one place.
Hub-and-Spoke Model:
Transitive Routing: Unlike VPC Peering, Transit Gateway allows traffic to pass through it to reach another destination (e.g., VPC A can talk to VPC C via the Gateway).
Scale: Supports up to 5,000 VPC attachments per gateway and massive throughput (up to 50 Gbps per VPC attachment).
Transit Gateway vs. VPC Peering
